 frequently contend, but a powerful political tool that created a framework within which few could argue successfully against the welfare policy changes. Legislation proposed in 2002 formalized this channel of policymaking, permitting the executive, as opposed to legislative, branches of federal and state governments to renegotiate social policies—an unprecedented change in American policymaking. This book provides unique insight into how social policy is made in the United States, and how that process is changing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAide socialexÉtats-Unis. 0aPublic welfarexUnited States. 0aPublic welfarezUnited States. 4aPolicy. 4aPolitics -- United States. 4aSociology -- Social Movements, Civil Society, and Politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476703340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767033/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles